<center>
<h1>Abstract Machine for SIS</h1>
</center>
<h2>
An abstract machine M<sub>sis</sub> for slow intelligence systems is defined as:

<p>
<font color=red>
M<sub>sis</sub> = { <i>P</i>, <i>S</i>, Po, cycle1, cycle2, ., cyclen}
</font>

<p>
Where <i>P</i> is the problem space, <i>S</i> the solution space, Po the initial problem set and cycle1, cycle2, ., cyclen the computation cycles.

<p>
The problem space <i>P</i> is a nonempty, enumerable set of problem elements p1, p2, ., pm.  A problem set Pk is a finite subset of <i>P</i>.  At least some of the problem elements in the problem space are also the solution elements. Therefore the solution space <i>S</i> is a nonempty subset of the problem space <i>P</i>. A solution set Sj is a finite subset of <i>S</i>.
